76561198064426221,Recommended,227220,31810083,Posted: 17 May,all,kgoblin,"I bought this way back when it wasn't free; and am replaying it now. I consider it worth the original selling price of ~$15 base, it being free makes it absolutly worth your time, so long as you have any taste at all for tower defense.Let's get the cons out of the way 1st:1. voice acting is horrible. Think Tony Wiseau monologue / old kung fu movie dub bad. You can kind of enjoy it for it's corniness, but it is very noticeable2. game is short. I had 4 hours on my 1st aborted playthru, and I was around 1/2 way in. Others seem to have beaten the game with both characters in 16 hours... so yeah 8 hour playthruIt's a tower defense game, but with some rather unorthodox gameplay & features.Rather than moving map to map, you play on the same map over and over, with different enemy waves & pathing. Playing on the same map might sound boring, but the map is very large, and they continue to add new sections to it as play progresses.Another unusual feature is that you will NEED to move your character around and actually fight things. The traps are an unusual mix of pure utility effects, one shot damage, and requiring manual activation thru the use key or shooting with the rifle. There is no aspect to play where you pick build the perfect meat grinder and then watch it go.The final unusual aspect is that some of the traps/structures cost money, and are permanent (until you activate them); this basically adds a long term base building element. Right now I have a centralized transport system set up with watchtowers, established over the course of 3 matches.The story & setting are very nice; if you have a taste for history & historical fiction especially. It's set around the 1850s in Canada, and plays on themes of Native American vs. Christian myth & folklore. The game mechanics nicely back up the setting & aesthetic, the traps all act & feel as you would expect a wolftrap, a bonfire, etc. to act, rather some game-ified infinite ammo turret, reskinned to be in the Canadian frontier.It isn't the best TD ever, but it is unique and satisfying, worth your time. Especially now that it's free."
