,Recommended,227220,10395715,"Posted: 8 June, 2014",all,MAzing87,"Just about an hr and a half into the tower defense game, Sang Froid Tales of Werewolves, and for $1.50 or 90% off asking price, this was a steal!! I kept my expectations very low. I thought, why would a $15 game be discounted more than 50%? I had to find out.It's about hunting werewolves! That alone had me interested. The story is about 2 brothers Jack and Jos, at odds with each other but have to work together to help save their sister Josephine, who is possessed by some evil spirit. You have to choose one of the brothers to control. Jack is the more strategic character that lays traps (according to the game difficulty, it's hard). Jos is the stronger of the two, an effective melee attacker (game difficulty, it's easy) to which I'm assuming that he has a bigger health bar. I chose Jack to play.What I was surprised about SF was how much you can do. From basic combat with wolves and werewolves, to planning out strategies to take on waves of enemies (mostly wolves and werewolves). Each successful night, gives you XP to improve your character, weapons, and traps. You can go up to level 15. Very well designed maps, menus, tutorials, and screens. The art direction follows more of the comic cut out look during the cutscenes. And it's nicely done. The controls are not the best, but very manageable. You can use a melee weapon from up close and ranged weapons from a distance. The best part about the combat is that you can use both types without overusing one or the other.I haven't played much strategy/base defense games before. The closest that I can think of is Assassin's Creed Revelation's tower defense (which was a bad addition to the franchise). Sang Froid Tales of Werewolves is a very good tower defense game. Get this game before the deal while on sale."
