,Recommended,227220,9236590,"Posted: 23 February, 2014",all,Juste,"This game is a different kind of tower defence.You use the night to set up traps to kill or impede the werewolves and other beasts, and then you have to finish what's left off yourself.This requires you to plan and make a strategy each night, which is really cool, thinking about how best to lure the max amout of werewolves into the most efficient trap and how many you can beat with your axe to save money.The story is charming and the game oozes charm and atmosphere, though the voice acting is fairly bad.If you want a different kind of tower defence game, and want to beat up werewolves with an axe, then this is the game for you!"
,Recommended,227220,9839623,"Posted: 17 April, 2014",all,Dr. Dogstreet,"Interesting fusion of strategy, tower defence and 3rd person action wrapped up with a quirky theme which is overall an enjoyable experience and worth a look if you want something different!The game has you taking the role of one of two brothers defending initially their cabin, but eventually a number of buildings and locations throughout a forest from ever increasing waves of wolves, werewolves and other mythical  creatures. Gameplay is split into two phases:Day Phase: This is basically the 'setup' you are presented with a map of the forest showing the spawn locations, number and targets of the various enemies you will face during the night. From here you can set traps, or place other structures to help you survive the night. You can visit shops to buy new equipment which the money you earn and spend skill points which are unlocked by levelling up your character to give you bonus abilities.Night Phase: During the night you must take control of your character to enact you plan by running around the forest, springing the traps you have set and taking on the enemies in combat (both gun based and melee).The game provides a good variety of enemies, each with different strengths and weaknesses to plan for, and a range of traps allowing you to pick your tactics. The 'Lumberjack' theme is nicely carried through the game in the art style of the menus and the soundtrack. The 3rd person combat is a little clunky, but is designed to keep you thinking tactically rather than just charging into a group with your axe.The game certainly has negative points which might put some people off. The story is overly complicated, fairly non-nonsensical and unnecessary. The voice acting/dialogue in the cut-scenes isn't amazing and in general I didn't like the way it was told, mostly in dull dialogue between characters. Occasionally there would be a cut scene represented in a kind of hand-drawn animation style (completely different to everything else) which actually worked really well and I can't help but think the game designers should have had a simpler story, but stuck to this style.The loading times are also quite long and although you can restart a mission at 'dusk' with all your traps in the same place, you still have to go back to the planning screen, start the night, go through the inventory screen, wait for the level to load  and click through any cut-scenes before you can make another attempt at a mission you failed, which gets annoying if you make a few mistakes early on in a mission."
,Recommended,227220,12541759,"Posted: 18 October, 2014",all,TBBle,"It's an interesting take on the Tower Defense with Combat Avatar hybrid style of game, giving a lot of choice in each level as to the emphasis you want to place on traps or melee combat. The cut-scenes really really need an 'advance dialog line' button, but I haven't quite brought myself to skip them unseen."
76561197969417125,Recommended,227220,353366,"Posted: 28 June, 2013",all,G00N3R,"Sangfroid is an action-tower defence game, like Orcs Must Die, but with more emphasis on tactical planning. It has some neat ideas that provide a fresh experience within the genre. You're a 19th century Canadian lumberjack, and your home is under attack by werewolves and other mystical creatures. Each level is split into two parts, day and night. During the day you can see which enemies you'll face, and which path they'll take. You can place traps, spend XP on upgrades, and visit town to buy weapons and equipment. Then you fight at night, using your traps and 3rd person combat. You can't place any new traps, your gun reloads slowly and melee attacks reduce your stamina. But this is good, because it really forces you to think ahead and carefully plan every move. The difficulty curve is nicely balanced. The story is good, but sadly the voice acting is awful, and graphics are not fantastic. Its very stable, and I got 9 hours from one playthrough, so I'm happy with value for money."
