,Recommended,227220,34939142,Posted: 13 September,all,Sabreman,"I am a lumberjack and I'm okay!I hunt all night and I chop alllllAAAGGHGHGSHSRHLLLL.. {killed by werewolf}Sang-Froid. Currently free for reasons I have no understanding of, but well worth the original full asking cost.I would try to include some critical realism about the game’s shortcomings, which do exist, but I literally write silly songs for this game when it goes on sale, so I’m just going to pretend this game is made entirely of awesome.I don't have to pretend hard. This game drips atmosphere and charm, even if the graphics seem a tad cartoony and the English voice acting is... passable, at best. Might be better in French; the game is fully subtitled in English anyway, and listening to Irish settlers in French Canada, one of whom has a Native accent for reasons that sort of make sense in the plot, should be stunning in at least two senses of that word.Be aware, as other reviewers have said, that the controls are going to seem... well, actually ARE, a bit clunky. I'm not sure if this is by design, or if the devs have made a virtue of an engine problem, but you aren't supposed to be a whiskey'd up Irish French Canadian ax ninja. (Note to self: suggest this for volume two when-if-ever the devs get around to it...!) In fact, I recommend that even beginners should start with Jaques, the brother who's better at hunting and not so great with an ax, anyway. He's designed to be harder to survive, but I find that adds an extra bit of tension to the game."
