,Recommended,227220,4012828,"Posted: 27 July, 2013",all,GamerLEN,"Normally I'm not one to like games where the antagonists are wolves, but I'm glad I got Sang-Froid. The music, ambience, and gameplay really do make you feel like you're in the 1800s.Its not just dark at night, it's pitch black, and you're outnumbered by wolves, werewolves, and more. The devil himself has come to town and ensnared the souls of everyone within. His goal is to corrupt the town's priest by bringing him your sister, whom he attempted to force himself on starting the events of this story.The music is very fitting to the setting, old fiddle music like you might've heard in an inn or bar back in those days, and the weaponry is very reminiscent of the olden days. No run and gun here, you have a flint lock rifle and reloading between shots takes time, a lot of time. You have to plan, you have to think on your feet, and you have to survive against all the monsters that hell can throw at you with nothing but your axe, your rifle, and your wits. The voice acting could be better, but otherwise this is definitely a game I could recommend."
76561197997993604,Recommended,227220,15565163,"Posted: 26 April, 2015",all,Vicboss,"This game is similar to a tower defense-style game such as Sanctum, where you place towers but are also controlling your character in third person from the battlefield. You don't actually place towers though, you place traps in an attempt to stop werewolves and other creatures of the night. Every day begins with you setting up your traps in a bird's eye view style. This leads to an interesting metagame where some traps cost AP (action points), but also money. It becomes difficult to balance setting up enough traps to win, while saving enough money and AP(which can be converted to money) to get better gear so later levels are easier. It's really fun trying to find the most cost-effective way in which to win a night. Also, your character fights with an axe and a musket."
