76561198013809346,Recommended,227220,9405507,"Posted: 9 March, 2014",all,The_Wise_Weasel,"Unique setting, simple but not dull combat as the combination of traps and weapons keeps things fresh... all in all, an excellent little effort. And I do mean little; it takes place over twenty days, meaning twenty levels, and then it's done. On the downside, the voice acting is mediocre, though not ""Oh dear sweet Cthulhu devour my mind that I may be free of this torment"" level (see: Disciples 3, Dawn of War). Seriously, though, you've set your game in frontier Canada, your main characters are French-Canadian, and you couldn't find any Quebecois to help with any of the voice acting? All the same, this game is a throwback to classics like The Horde and its newer versions in Orcs Must Die and other tower defense FPSs, and is fun, compelling, and challenging. Totally worth one's $15."
76561198034432601,Recommended,227220,9436851,"Posted: 12 March, 2014",all,MandaPanda ʕ﻿ •ᴥ•ʔ,"Sang-froid: Tales of Werewolves is a action/strategy game that was surprisingly entertaining. I did not expect to fall in love with this game as much as I did. You play one of the two feuding brothers who have to work together to protect their sister from the Devil. The story takes place in a snowy village in Canada during the 19th Century.The game has a great balance between action and strategy.  During the day you can go to town, buy a better musket and/or axe to fight the werewolves with.  There are also health, stamina, increase damage potions and a lot more.  You can head to the convent to have one of the nuns bless your axe or bullets which increases your damage to the werewolves but this will eat into some of your money.  You can use the rest of your money to then buy traps and set up how you are going to defeat the waves of werewolves that come in the night.  Anything that gets passed your trap you will have to shoot or strike with an axe.At first you just start by protecting the house your sister is resting in but the game eventually adds four more buildings that you have to protect, adding more of a challenge.  In addition, the game eventually adds a smell factor into your planning.  Your scent is carried by the wind, which changes direction everyday.  Your scent can either ruin or better your strategy depending on how you use it.  The game adds another mechanic that is called Fear Factor.  With this you are able to intimidate the wolves and be able to handle multiple wolves at a time.  In the beginning it's not that complicated and there is not much planning you have to do but as the story progresses the more time you spend planning out your strategy.A feature I liked about the game is that if something doesn't go right during the night and wolves start to overwhelm you, you can go back and make minor tweaks to your strategy and try new things out.  Towards the end there are a couple of days that are tough and you will have to do some trial and error strategy’s but I really enjoyed that part as well.At the start of the game you choose which brother you would like to use.  You are given a basic musket and a basic axe.  You can upgrade them using your money and also improve it's skills with a skill tree.  As you gain EXP (by killing wolves) you will gain levels and get a skill point for every level you earn.  You can then spend that skill point into a skill tree to improve your gun, axe, health, stamina, fear factor, or traps.The music in the game is really strange but in a good way.  It's very catchy and I enjoyed it as it went well with the time and theme of the game.The voice acting is... not the best... unfortunately.  I think it could have been quite a lot better.  The voice acting isn't a deal breaker for me though, I can get passed it and just listen to the story and enjoy the gameplay.Bad voice acting aside, the game is wonderful and I can't wait for Tome II to come out.  I really enjoyed it, the story is good, the combat is fun and planning out your night I found to be the funnest part.  I will be replaying it again as the other brother."
